2025-12-12 | Maximum Number of Visible People in a Line

	Question
Given an array arr[] of heights,  
return the maximum number of people that any person can see (including themselves).

	Approach
1.	The visibility rule means taller or equal-height people block the view.
2.	For each person, count how many people they can see to the **left** and **right**.
3.	Use a **monotonic decreasing stack** to efficiently compute visibility.
4.	Left side computation:
	-	Traverse from left to right.
	-	Pop all shorter people from the stack (they are visible).
	-	If the stack is not empty afterward, one taller/equal person is also visible.
5.	Right side computation:
	-	Traverse from right to left using the same logic.
6.	For each index i:
		totalVisible = leftVisible[i] + rightVisible[i] + 1
	(+1 accounts for the person themselves)
7.	The answer is the maximum totalVisible over all i.
8.	Time Complexity: O(n)  
   Space Complexity: O(n)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    int maxPeopleVisible(vector<int>& arr) {
        int n = arr.size();
        vector<int> left(n, 0), right(n, 0);
        stack<int> st;

        // Count visible people to the left
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            while (!st.empty() && st.top() < arr[i]) {
                st.pop();
                left[i]++;
            }
            if (!st.empty())
                left[i]++;
            st.push(arr[i]);
        }

        while (!st.empty()) st.pop();

        // Count visible people to the right
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            while (!st.empty() && st.top() < arr[i]) {
                st.pop();
                right[i]++;
            }
            if (!st.empty())
                right[i]++;
            st.push(arr[i]);
        }

        int ans = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            ans = max(ans, left[i] + right[i] + 1);
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
